An abdominal hernia occurs when an organ or tissue protrudes through a weak spot in the abdominal muscles. It often appears as a bulge in the abdomen.

A lung abscess is a localized collection of pus within the lung tissue caused by a bacterial infection. It often results from aspiration (inhaling food, liquid, or vomit), especially in individuals with impaired consciousness or swallowing difficulty. It can also develop as a complication of pneumonia or bronchial obstruction. Symptoms typically include fever, cough with foul-smelling or bloody sputum, chest pain, and fatigue.

Achalasia is a rare disorder that makes it hard for food and liquid to pass into the stomach from the esophagus. This happens when the muscles of the esophagus don’t work properly and the lower esophageal sphincter (a valve at the bottom of the esophagus) doesn’t relax as it should. Symptoms may include difficulty swallowing, chest discomfort, regurgitation of food, and weight loss.
column380: Eat slowly and chew food well
column382: Avoid very cold or hot foods

column379: Actinic keratosis is a rough, scaly patch on the skin caused by years of sun exposure. It most often appears on the face, lips, ears, back of the hands, forearms, scalp, or neck. Though it's not cancerous, it can sometimes develop into skin cancer if left untreated.

Acute otitis media is a sudden infection of the middle ear, often caused by bacteria or viruses. It is common in children and may result in ear pain, fever, and temporary hearing loss. Fluid may also build up behind the eardrum.
column383: Stay up to date with vaccinations

column379: Acute pancreatitis is a sudden inflammation of the pancreas that can cause severe abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fever. It’s often triggered by gallstones or excessive alcohol use and may require hospitalization in severe cases.

Acute sinusitis is a short-term inflammation of the sinuses, typically caused by a viral infection. It results in symptoms like facial pain or pressure, nasal congestion, runny nose, headache, and sometimes fever. Most cases resolve on their own within a couple of weeks.

Alopecia is the loss of hair from the scalp or other areas of the body. It can occur suddenly and in small patches. The most common form, alopecia areata, is an autoimmune condition where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks hair follicles. It can affect anyone and may vary from small patches of hair loss to complete baldness.

column380: Stay active with gentle exercises and massages

column379: Asthma is a chronic respiratory condition that causes inflammation and narrowing of the airways, leading to difficulty in breathing. Common symptoms include wheezing, shortness of breath, coughing, and chest tightness, especially at night or early in the morning. Asthma can be triggered by allergens, irritants, respiratory infections, and other environmental factors.
column383: Pay attention to local air quality reports

column379: Astigmatism is a common refractive error in the eyes, where the cornea or lens is irregularly shaped. This irregular shape causes blurred or distorted vision at all distances. People with astigmatism may experience eye strain, headaches, and difficulty seeing clearly, especially at night.

Atelectasis occurs when a portion of the lung collapses, leading to reduced air exchange in that area. This condition can result from blocked airways, pressure from outside the lung, or surfactant deficiency. Symptoms include difficulty breathing, chest pain, and coughing. It can occur due to various reasons, including surgery, pneumonia, or foreign object aspiration.

Atrial fibrillation (AFib) is a type of irregular heartbeat (arrhythmia) that can lead to blood clots, stroke, heart failure, and other heart-related complications. The heart's upper chambers (atria) beat chaotically and out of sync with the lower chambers, causing an irregular and often rapid heart rate. Symptoms may include palpitations, shortness of breath, dizziness, and fatigue.

Atrophic vaginitis, also known as vaginal atrophy, occurs when the vaginal walls become thin, dry, and inflamed due to a decrease in estrogen levels, commonly during menopause. It can lead to discomfort, pain during intercourse, vaginal dryness, and urinary symptoms such as increased frequency of urination.

ADHD is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by symptoms of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity. Individuals with ADHD may struggle with focusing on tasks, sitting still, and controlling impulses, which can affect their performance in school, work, and daily activities. It is commonly diagnosed in childhood, though symptoms may persist into adulthood.

Bipolar disorder is a mental health condition marked by extreme mood swings that include emotional highs (mania or hypomania) and lows (depression). These shifts can impact a person’s ability to function in daily life. Mania includes increased energy, impulsivity, and grandiosity, while depression involves feelings of sadness, hopelessness, and low energy. Bipolar disorder can affect work, relationships, and general well-being.

Bladder disorders encompass a variety of conditions that affect the function of the bladder, including urinary incontinence, overactive bladder, and urinary retention. Symptoms may include frequent urination, urgency, difficulty starting or stopping urination, and discomfort or pain during urination. These conditions can be caused by infections, nerve issues, or underlying diseases like diabetes or neurological disorders.

A bone spur of the calcaneus, also known as a heel spur, is a bony growth that forms on the heel bone (calcaneus), often due to excessive pressure or stress on the foot. It is commonly associated with plantar fasciitis and can cause heel pain, particularly when walking or standing for long periods. In some cases, bone spurs may develop without symptoms.

Bursitis is the inflammation of a bursa, a small fluid-filled sac that acts as a cushion between bones and soft tissues such as muscles or tendons. It commonly affects areas like the shoulders, elbows, hips, or knees. Symptoms include pain, swelling, and restricted movement in the affected area. Bursitis can be caused by repetitive motion, injury, or prolonged pressure on a joint.

Cellulitis of the mouth refers to a bacterial infection in the soft tissues of the mouth or surrounding areas. It often results in swelling, redness, pain, and sometimes fever. An abscess in the mouth is a pocket of pus that forms due to infection, commonly caused by tooth decay, gum disease, or trauma to the mouth. It can cause localized swelling, pain, and difficulty swallowing or breathing if severe.

Cerebral Palsy (CP) is a group of neurological disorders that affect movement, coordination, and muscle tone. It is caused by brain damage that occurs before, during, or shortly after birth. The severity of symptoms varies, but common characteristics include difficulty with motor skills, abnormal gait, muscle stiffness or weakness, and, in some cases, developmental delays or intellectual impairments.

Cervical Spondylosis is a condition caused by age-related wear and tear on the cervical spine (neck). It often results in the degeneration of discs and joints in the neck, leading to symptoms such as neck pain, stiffness, headaches, and in some cases, numbness or tingling in the arms or hands. The condition can be exacerbated by poor posture or repetitive neck movements.

A chalazion is a small, painless lump or cyst that appears on the eyelid due to a blocked oil gland. It typically develops when the meibomian gland becomes obstructed, leading to inflammation. While it may be discomforting or cause mild irritation, it usually does not affect vision. Chalazia may go away on their own, but persistent ones may need medical intervention.
column381: Avoid squeezing or popping the lump

column383: Stay isolated and avoid public places

column379: Choledocholithiasis is a condition where one or more gallstones are present in the common bile duct. This condition can block the bile duct, leading to symptoms like jaundice, pain in the upper right abdomen, nausea, and vomiting. It may also cause inflammation or infection of the bile duct, known as cholangitis. Treatment often involves removing the gallstones through endoscopy or surgery.

Cholesteatoma is an abnormal growth of skin cells in the middle ear, which can damage the ear bones, lead to hearing loss, and potentially cause infection. It usually develops as a result of chronic ear infections. Symptoms can include a persistent ear discharge, ear fullness, and hearing loss. Treatment typically involves surgical removal of the cholesteatoma.
column381: Avoid inserting objects in the ear

column379: Chorioretinitis is an inflammation of the choroid and retina in the eye, often caused by an infection, autoimmune disorders, or exposure to toxins. This condition can lead to blurred vision, pain, and light sensitivity. Chorioretinitis can be either infectious or non-infectious, and early treatment is important to prevent permanent vision loss.

Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is a gradual loss of kidney function over time. The kidneys are responsible for filtering waste and excess fluids from the blood, and when they become damaged, waste products can build up in the body. CKD can be caused by conditions like diabetes, high blood pressure, and other chronic diseases. It may lead to kidney failure if not managed properly.
column382: Monitor blood pressure and blood sugar

column379: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) is a progressive lung disease that makes it difficult to breathe. It includes conditions like emphysema and chronic bronchitis. The primary cause is long-term exposure to irritants that damage the lungs and airways, particularly smoking. Symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, chronic cough, and frequent respiratory infections. COPD can be managed, but it worsens over time.

Chronic Pain Disorder is a condition where pain persists for months or even years, often without an identifiable cause. It can affect various areas of the body and may result from injuries, medical conditions, or even psychological factors. This condition can lead to significant physical and emotional distress, often resulting in fatigue, depression, and anxiety. Managing chronic pain typically involves a combination of medications, therapy, and lifestyle changes.

Chronic Sinusitis is a condition where the sinuses remain inflamed and swollen for a prolonged period, usually over 12 weeks, despite treatment. It can lead to difficulty breathing through the nose, nasal congestion, facial pain, and a decreased sense of smell. It often occurs due to infections, allergies, or other factors that block the sinus passages, preventing drainage and leading to persistent inflammation. Managing chronic sinusitis involves treating underlying causes and alleviating symptoms.
column383: Practice nasal irrigation by using a saline nasal spray

column379: Cirrhosis is a liver disease characterized by long-term damage to the liver, leading to the scarring of liver tissue. This scarring impairs the liver's ability to function properly, affecting vital processes such as detoxification, protein synthesis, and bile production. Cirrhosis can be caused by factors such as chronic alcohol consumption, viral infections (like hepatitis), or non-alcoholic fatty liver disease. In the early stages, cirrhosis may have few symptoms, but as it progresses, it can lead to complications such as liver failure, internal bleeding, and increased risk of liver cancer.

Coagulation disorders are conditions where the blood does not clot properly, leading to excessive bleeding. This can occur due to deficiencies in certain clotting factors in the blood, such as in hemophilia or vitamin K deficiency. Coagulation disorders may be inherited or acquired, and they can cause symptoms like easy bruising, prolonged bleeding from cuts, and internal bleeding. If left untreated, bleeding disorders can result in serious complications, including joint damage, organ damage, or life-threatening hemorrhages.
column381: Use soft toothbrushes and floss gently

column379: Colonic polyps are growths that form on the inner lining of the colon or rectum. While most polyps are benign, some can develop into colon cancer over time. They often do not cause symptoms, but larger polyps may result in rectal bleeding, changes in bowel movements, or abdominal pain. Regular screening, such as colonoscopies, is crucial for detecting and removing polyps early, reducing the risk of cancer.

Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS) is a chronic condition characterized by severe, persistent pain typically affecting an arm or a leg. It often develops after an injury, surgery, stroke, or heart attack, but the pain experienced is usually out of proportion to the original injury. Common symptoms include burning or throbbing pain, swelling, changes in skin temperature and color, and decreased mobility of the affected limb. The exact cause is not fully understood, but it involves abnormal responses in the nervous system.

A concussion is a mild traumatic brain injury caused by a blow, bump, or jolt to the head that disrupts normal brain function. It may result in symptoms like confusion, headache, dizziness, nausea, blurred vision, and difficulty concentrating. While most concussions are not life-threatening, they still require proper care and rest to avoid further complications. Symptoms can last for days to weeks, and a second concussion before full recovery can be dangerous.
column383: Avoid loud noises and bright lights

column379: Conductive hearing loss happens when sound waves cannot effectively travel through the outer ear, eardrum, or middle ear. This can result from ear infections, fluid buildup, earwax blockage, or damage to the ear bones. Unlike sensorineural hearing loss, conductive hearing loss often improves with treatment or intervention and may be temporary. Common symptoms include muffled hearing, ear discomfort, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.
column380: Avoid inserting objects into your ears
column383: Use warm compresses for mild ear discomfort

column379: Conversion disorder, also known as Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder, involves neurological symptoms—such as paralysis, tremors, or non-epileptic seizures—that cannot be explained by medical conditions. These symptoms are thought to be linked to psychological stress or trauma. The symptoms are real and can cause significant distress or problems in functioning, even though no physical cause is found.

A cornea infection, or keratitis, is an inflammation of the cornea — the clear, dome-shaped surface that covers the front of the eye. It can be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, or parasites, often resulting from contact lens use, eye injuries, or contaminated water exposure. Symptoms include eye redness, pain, blurry vision, and sensitivity to light. If left untreated, it may lead to vision loss.
column380: Wash hands before touching your eyes or face
column381: Avoid using expired or dirty contact lenses
column382: Wear protective eyewear in dusty or risky environments

column379: Corneal disorders refer to a group of conditions that affect the cornea, the transparent front layer of the eye. These include abrasions, dystrophies, infections, degenerations, and scars. Such issues can lead to blurred vision, eye pain, tearing, redness, and light sensitivity. The causes vary and may include genetics, trauma, or infections.
column380: Avoid touching or rubbing your eyes unnecessarily
column381: Use clean water to rinse eyes if exposed to dust or irritants
column383: Ensure good hygiene with eye makeup or contact lenses

column379: Coronary atherosclerosis is the hardening and narrowing of the coronary arteries due to plaque buildup. These arteries supply blood to the heart, and when blocked, it can reduce oxygen flow, potentially leading to chest pain (angina), heart attack, or other cardiovascular problems. It typically develops over time due to high cholesterol, smoking, poor diet, or lack of exercise.
column380: Engage in light daily physical activity
column381: Choose meals with less saturated fat and salt
column382: Avoid smoking or exposure to secondhand smoke
column383: Try to manage daily stress levels

column379: Cranial nerve palsy refers to a condition where one or more of the twelve cranial nerves that control movement and sensation in the face and head become weakened or paralyzed. This can lead to symptoms like facial drooping, difficulty swallowing, vision problems, or loss of facial sensation. Causes can include infections, injuries, tumors, or underlying neurological conditions.
column381: Practice good hygiene to prevent infections

column379: A crushing injury occurs when a body part is subjected to a high degree of pressure, typically after being squeezed between two heavy objects. This can cause damage to muscles, bones, blood vessels, and nerves, and in severe cases, may lead to complications like compartment syndrome or tissue death.
column380: Use proper safety gear at work or during physical activities
column381: Be cautious around heavy machinery or vehicles
column382: Avoid overcrowded or unstable storage areas
column383: Take breaks when lifting or moving heavy items

column379: Cryptococcosis is a fungal infection caused by Cryptococcus species, most commonly Cryptococcus neoformans. It primarily affects the lungs and central nervous system, especially in individuals with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS. The infection can lead to pneumonia-like symptoms or even meningitis if it spreads to the brain.
column380: Avoid areas with bird droppings (especially pigeon nests)
column381: Wear a mask when cleaning dusty or moldy areas
column382: Practice good hygiene and handwashing habits
column383: Maintain a healthy immune system through proper diet and rest

column379: Cryptorchidism, also known as undescended testes, occurs when one or both of a male infant's testes fail to descend into the scrotum before birth. It is a common condition in newborns, particularly premature infants. If left untreated, it can lead to infertility, testicular cancer, and other complications. Treatment usually involves surgery, but early intervention is important.
column381: Maintain a healthy weight and avoid environmental toxins
column383: Follow doctor's advice on treatment options

column379: Cysticercosis is an infection caused by the larvae of Taenia solium, a type of tapeworm. It occurs when a person ingests tapeworm eggs, which then hatch into larvae that travel to various tissues in the body, including muscles, skin, and, most commonly, the brain (neurocysticercosis). Symptoms can include seizures, headaches, and vision problems. Treatment typically involves anti-parasitic medications and sometimes surgery for severe cases.
column382: Avoid consuming unclean water or food

column379: Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) is a condition where a blood clot forms in one of the deep veins, typically in the legs. The clot can block blood flow and cause swelling, pain, and redness. If the clot breaks loose, it can travel to the lungs, causing a life-threatening condition known as a pulmonary embolism (PE). DVT is often linked to prolonged immobility, recent surgery, or certain medical conditions that affect blood clotting.
column383: Maintain a healthy weight and diet

column379: Eating disorders are mental health conditions characterized by unhealthy eating habits, such as extreme restriction, overeating, or purging. Common types include anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, and binge-eating disorder. These conditions can have serious physical and emotional effects and often stem from body image issues, stress, or emotional distress.

Emphysema is a chronic lung condition and a form of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD). It involves the gradual destruction of the air sacs (alveoli) in the lungs, which reduces the surface area for gas exchange and makes it hard to breathe. The primary cause is long-term exposure to airborne irritants, especially cigarette smoke.
column382: Stay indoors on days with poor air quality

column379: Empyema is a condition in which pus collects in the space between the lung and the inner surface of the chest wall (pleural space). It usually occurs as a complication of pneumonia or chest infections, leading to inflammation and infection in the pleural cavity. Without treatment, it can become life-threatening.

Endometriosis is a condition where tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus grows outside the uterus, typically on the ovaries, fallopian tubes, or the tissue lining the pelvis. This can cause pain, especially during menstruation, and may lead to infertility.
column380: Maintain a balanced diet with anti-inflammatory foods like fruits, vegetables, and omega-3 rich foods
column381: Applying a heating pad to the abdomen may help alleviate menstrual cramps and pelvic pain

column383: Regular physical activity can help reduce pain

column379: Endophthalmitis is a severe inflammation of the interior of the eye, often caused by an infection. It can occur after eye surgery, trauma, or as a complication from infections spreading through the bloodstream. If not treated promptly, it may lead to vision loss.
column380: Avoid touching or rubbing your eyes

column379: Esophageal cancer is a type of cancer that occurs in the esophagus—the long, hollow tube that carries food from the throat to the stomach. Symptoms may include difficulty swallowing, chest pain, weight loss, and persistent cough. Early detection is key to improving outcomes.
column380: Avoid tobacco and limit alcohol use
column381: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits and vegetables

column379: Eye alignment disorders, such as strabismus, occur when the eyes do not line up properly and point in different directions. One eye may turn in, out, up, or down while the other looks straight ahead. This condition can affect depth perception and lead to double vision or eye strain if left untreated.
column381: Limit screen time and take frequent breaks
column382: Ensure proper lighting when reading or working
column383: Encourage outdoor play or natural viewing in children

column379: Female infertility of unknown cause, also called unexplained infertility, is diagnosed when a woman has not become pregnant after one year of regular unprotected intercourse, and no clear medical reason can be identified after standard fertility testing. It may be influenced by subtle hormonal imbalances, lifestyle factors, or yet undetectable reproductive system issues.
column380: Maintain a balanced diet and healthy weight
column381: Reduce stress through activities like yoga or meditation
column383: Track menstrual cycles and ovulation naturally

column379: Fetal Alcohol Syndrome is a condition that results from alcohol exposure during pregnancy. It can cause a range of physical, behavioral, and cognitive issues in the child, such as facial abnormalities, poor growth, learning difficulties, and problems with memory and attention. FAS is part of a group of conditions known as Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorders (FASDs).
column382: Take prenatal vitamins with folic acid
column383: Stay informed about healthy pregnancy practices

column379: Fibromyalgia is a long-term condition characterized by widespread muscle pain, fatigue, sleep disturbances, and cognitive difficulties (often called "fibro fog"). The exact cause is unknown, but it may be linked to how the brain processes pain signals. It’s more common in women and can significantly affect quality of life, although it is not life-threatening.
column381: Do light stretching or yoga regularly
column382: Reduce stress through mindfulness or relaxation techniques

column379: Flat feet (also known as fallen arches) is a condition where the arches of the feet are flattened, allowing the entire sole to touch the ground when standing. It can be present from birth or develop over time due to age, injury, or stress on the foot. While often painless, flat feet can sometimes lead to discomfort in the feet, ankles, or knees.

column379: This condition occurs when a non-food object is swallowed and becomes lodged in the digestive tract. It is more common in children but can happen at any age. While many foreign objects pass through naturally, some may cause pain, obstruction, or internal damage, requiring medical attention.
column380: Keep small objects out of reach of children
column383: Educate children on safe eating and play habits

column379: This condition occurs when an object is unintentionally or intentionally inserted and retained inside the vagina. It’s more commonly seen in children or individuals with cognitive impairments but can occur in adults as well. Symptoms might include unusual discharge, bleeding, discomfort, or foul odor. If not removed, it can cause infection or injury.
column381: Teach children appropriate hygiene and body awareness
column383: Seek guidance when using internal hygiene products

column379: A fracture of the arm refers to a break in one of the bones of the upper limb — typically the humerus, radius, or ulna. It can result from trauma like a fall, direct blow, or accident. Symptoms include severe pain, swelling, bruising, inability to move the arm, and sometimes a visible deformity. Treatment usually involves immobilization, pain relief, and in some cases, surgery.
column381: Ensure safe home and work environments
column382: Maintain bone health with a balanced diet

column379: A hand fracture involves a break in one or more bones of the hand, such as the metacarpals or phalanges. It can occur from direct trauma like falls, sports injuries, or accidents. Common symptoms include swelling, bruising, pain, and difficulty moving the fingers or hand. Treatment often involves splinting or casting, and in more severe cases, surgical intervention may be required.
column380: Avoid using the affected hand for heavy tasks
column382: Use protective equipment in sports or risky activities

column379: Glaucoma is a group of eye diseases that damage the optic nerve, often due to high intraocular pressure. It is one of the leading causes of blindness worldwide. Early stages may not show symptoms, but over time, it can lead to vision loss. Regular eye exams are essential for early detection and management, which may include eye drops or surgical procedures.
column380: Wear protective eyewear to protect eyes from injury

column379: Hashimoto thyroiditis is an autoimmune disorder where the immune system attacks the thyroid gland, leading to hypothyroidism (an underactive thyroid). This condition can result in symptoms like fatigue, weight gain, depression, and sensitivity to cold. It's commonly diagnosed through blood tests that check thyroid hormone levels and antibodies. Treatment usually involves thyroid hormone replacement therapy.
column380: Include iodine-rich foods like fish, dairy, and seaweed to support thyroid function, but avoid excessive iodine in your diet
column381: Monitor thyroid levels regularly through blood tests

column379: A headache after a lumbar puncture, also known as a spinal tap, is a common complication. This type of headache typically develops within a few hours to a couple of days after the procedure and is caused by a decrease in cerebrospinal fluid pressure. Symptoms may include a dull, throbbing headache that worsens when standing or sitting. Treatment often involves rest, hydration, and sometimes a procedure called an epidural blood patch to seal any leaks in the spinal fluid.
column380: Drink plenty of fluids and avoid physical exertion
column381: Lying flat on your back can relieve pressure
column383: Consult your doctor if symptoms persist

column379: Heart block refers to a condition where the electrical signals in the heart are delayed or blocked, affecting the normal heart rhythm. It can occur in varying degrees: first-degree, second-degree, and third-degree heart block, with third-degree being the most severe. Symptoms may include dizziness, fatigue, chest pain, and fainting. Treatment depends on the severity of the condition and may involve medications or the placement of a pacemaker in more severe cases.
column380: Eat a balanced diet to support heart health, including foods low in sodium, and rich in potassium and magnesium

column379: Hemarthrosis is the medical term for bleeding into a joint. It typically occurs due to an injury, but it can also be caused by underlying conditions such as hemophilia or other clotting disorders. Symptoms include joint pain, swelling, warmth, and limited range of motion. If left untreated, repeated episodes can lead to joint damage and long-term mobility issues.

Herpangina is a viral infection, commonly caused by the coxsackievirus, affecting children. It is characterized by fever, sore throat, and the appearance of small, painful sores or ulcers in the back of the mouth and throat. While it is typically self-limiting and resolves within a week, symptoms can cause significant discomfort during the illness.
column380: Drink plenty of fluids such as water, ice pops, and clear broths to stay hydrated

column379: Hyperhidrosis is a condition characterized by excessive sweating beyond what is necessary to regulate body temperature. It can affect various parts of the body, including the palms, feet, underarms, and face. The exact cause may be unknown (primary hyperhidrosis), or it can be linked to another condition (secondary hyperhidrosis). It may cause embarrassment or discomfort but can be managed with various treatments.
column381: Look for stronger, clinical-strength antiperspirants to apply to affected areas, especially before bedtime
column382: Regularly dry off areas of excess sweating with a towel to avoid skin irritation
column383: Bathe regularly to remove sweat and bacteria

column379: Hyperkalemia refers to an abnormally high level of potassium in the blood. Potassium is an essential mineral that helps with muscle function and heart rhythm. When potassium levels rise too high, it can cause serious issues, such as irregular heartbeats or even cardiac arrest. Hyperkalemia can be caused by kidney problems, certain medications, or excessive potassium intake.
column381: Drink enough fluids, particularly water, to support kidney function and help balance electrolytes
column383: Avoid potassium supplements unless specifically recommended by a healthcare provider

column379: Hypertrophic Obstructive Cardiomyopathy (HOCM) is a condition where the heart muscle becomes abnormally thickened (hypertrophied), which can make it harder for the heart to pump blood effectively. This thickening typically occurs in the septum, the wall between the two chambers of the heart, and may obstruct blood flow, leading to heart-related symptoms. HOCM is often inherited and can result in heart palpitations, dizziness, and, in severe cases, sudden cardiac arrest.

column383: Be vigilant about changes in symptoms like dizziness, shortness of breath, or chest pain

column379: Hypothyroidism is a condition where the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormones. These hormones regulate the body's metabolism, and when levels are low, it can slow down various bodily functions. Symptoms of hypothyroidism can include fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, dry skin, hair loss, and constipation. It is typically diagnosed through blood tests and can be managed with hormone replacement therapy.
column380: Focus on a well-balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins
column381: Engage in moderate exercise, such as walking or swimming
column382: Practice relaxation techniques like deep breathing, meditation, or yoga to help reduce stress

column379: Idiopathic nonmenstrual bleeding refers to abnormal bleeding from the uterus that is not associated with the menstrual cycle. The exact cause is unknown (idiopathic), but it can result from hormonal imbalances, stress, or other underlying health conditions. Symptoms include irregular bleeding between periods, heavy periods, or spotting. A healthcare provider typically diagnoses this condition after ruling out other potential causes.
column380: Monitor your menstrual cycle and any unusual bleeding patterns to help identify any changes or abnormalities
column383: Limit the use of products that may irritate the genital area

column379: Indigestion, or dyspepsia, is a common condition characterized by discomfort or pain in the upper abdomen, often accompanied by bloating, nausea, and burping. It can be triggered by overeating, consuming spicy or fatty foods, stress, or certain medications. Indigestion is usually temporary but can become a recurrent issue if not managed properly.
column380: Try eating smaller, more frequent meals to prevent overloading the stomach and causing discomfort
column381: Reduce intake of fatty, spicy, and acidic foods that can irritate the digestive system and trigger indigestion
column382: Drink plenty of water throughout the day to help with digestion and prevent dehydration, which can worsen symptoms
column383: Wait at least 2-3 hours before lying down after meals to prevent acid reflux and improve digestion

column379: Induced abortion is the medical or surgical termination of a pregnancy before the fetus can survive independently. It may be performed for various reasons, including personal choice, health risks to the mother, or fetal abnormalities. Depending on the stage of pregnancy, different procedures may be used, and it's typically done in a clinical setting for safety.
column382: Talk to a trusted person or counselor for emotional support

column379: An infection of an open wound occurs when bacteria or other pathogens enter a break in the skin, causing redness, swelling, warmth, pus, and pain. If left untreated, the infection can spread and lead to more serious complications. Prompt and proper wound care is essential for healing and preventing infection.
column380: Rinse with clean water and gently remove dirt to reduce the risk of bacteria entering
column381: Use a sterile bandage to protect the area from dirt and bacteria
column382: Keeping the wound clean and dry helps prevent bacterial growth
column383: Don’t pick or scratch the area to prevent introducing new bacteria

column379: Infectious gastroenteritis is an inflammation of the stomach and intestines caused by viruses, bacteria, or parasites. It leads to symptoms like diarrhea, vomiting, stomach cramps, and sometimes fever. It spreads through contaminated food, water, or contact with infected individuals. Most cases resolve on their own with rest and hydration.

An ingrown toenail occurs when the edge of a toenail grows into the surrounding skin, usually on the big toe. It can cause redness, swelling, pain, and sometimes infection. It may result from improper nail trimming, tight footwear, or injury to the toe.

An abdominal injury involves trauma to the stomach or surrounding area, which can be caused by blunt force (like a fall or car accident) or penetrating wounds (like a stab). It may affect internal organs and can range from minor bruises to serious internal bleeding.

An injury to the arm can range from minor bruises and sprains to more serious conditions like fractures or dislocations. It may occur due to falls, direct blows, or repetitive strain and can affect the muscles, bones, joints, or skin.
column380: Limit movement to allow healing and avoid further damage
column381: Helps reduce pain and swelling in the first 48 hours
column382: Keep the arm raised to minimize swelling
column383: Provides comfort and stability during the healing process

column379: Injuries to the finger are common and can include cuts, bruises, sprains, fractures, or dislocations. These often result from accidents during sports, work, or daily activities. Prompt and gentle care can help avoid complications.
column380: Keep the finger clean and dry
column382: Avoid using the injured finger excessively
column383: Protect with a soft bandage or splint (if needed)

column379: Hand injuries can result from trauma, overuse, or accidents and may include cuts, sprains, bruises, fractures, or burns. Since the hand is used constantly, even minor injuries can affect daily activities and should be treated with care.
column382: Keep any wounds clean and covered

column379: A hip injury can occur due to falls, overuse, or direct impact, and may involve bruises, sprains, dislocations, or fractures. It can affect mobility and balance, and should be monitored carefully, especially in older adults.
column380: Avoid putting weight on the affected side
column383: Use cushions or pillows while sitting or sleeping

column379: A knee injury can result from a fall, sudden twist, sports activity, or overuse. It may involve ligaments, tendons, cartilage, or the kneecap. Common symptoms include swelling, pain, stiffness, or difficulty walking.
column380: Rest the knee and avoid intense activities
column383: Use a soft knee support or wrap

column379: A shoulder injury can occur from falls, accidents, or repetitive movements, causing damage to muscles, ligaments, or the rotator cuff. Common signs include pain, limited movement, swelling, or bruising around the shoulder area.
column380: Rest the shoulder to avoid further strain
column383: Use a shoulder brace or wrap for support

column379: Injury to the trunk involves damage to the chest, abdomen, or lower back area due to trauma such as falls, accidents, or heavy impacts. Symptoms may include pain, bruising, difficulty breathing, or abdominal discomfort. Severity can range from mild bruises to more serious internal injuries.
column380: Rest and avoid heavy lifting or strenuous activities
column381: Apply a cold compress to reduce swelling
column382: Wear a supportive brace or bandage if recommended
column383: Monitor for any signs of severe discomfort, breathing difficulties, or dizziness

column379: Intestinal malabsorption occurs when the small intestine is unable to properly absorb nutrients from food, leading to deficiencies in vitamins, minerals, and other essential nutrients. Causes may include conditions such as celiac disease, Crohn's disease, or lactose intolerance. Symptoms often include diarrhea, weight loss, bloating, and fatigue.
column381: Avoid foods that trigger symptoms (e.g., gluten, dairy, etc.)
column382: Stay hydrated by drinking plenty of fluids
column383: Consider a multivitamin supplement (with guidance from a healthcare provider)

column379: Intracranial hemorrhage (ICH) refers to bleeding within the brain or the surrounding spaces. It can result from trauma, high blood pressure, aneurysms, or blood vessel abnormalities. Symptoms vary depending on the location and severity of the bleed but often include headaches, vomiting, confusion, weakness, or seizures. Immediate medical attention is necessary.
column380: Avoid strenuous activities and heavy lifting
column382: Eat a brain-healthy diet by focusing on foods rich in omega-3 fatty acids, antioxidants, and vitamins that support brain health, such as leafy greens and fish

column379: Bowel ischemia occurs when there is a reduced blood flow to the intestines, leading to damage or death of intestinal tissue. This condition can be caused by blockages in blood vessels, such as blood clots or narrowing of the arteries. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, bloating, nausea, vomiting, and bloody stools. Prompt medical intervention is crucial to prevent severe complications.

column379: Juvenile Rheumatoid Arthritis, also known as Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis (JIA), is a type of arthritis that affects children under the age of 16. It causes persistent joint pain, swelling, and stiffness. Some children may experience symptoms for only a few months, while others may have symptoms for many years. The exact cause is unknown but is believed to involve an autoimmune response where the body attacks its own joint tissues.
column382: Include nutrient-rich foods to support overall health and potentially reduce inflammation

column379: Lice are tiny, wingless parasitic insects that live on the human scalp and feed on blood. They are highly contagious and spread through close personal contact or sharing personal items like combs, hats, or towels. While lice aren’t dangerous and don’t spread disease, they can cause intense itching and scalp irritation due to their bites and the body’s reaction to them.
column381: Tie up long hair in public
column382: Regularly wash and dry bedding on high heat

column379: Liver cancer originates in the tissues of the liver, most commonly as hepatocellular carcinoma. It may develop due to chronic infections like hepatitis B or C, cirrhosis, or long-term alcohol use. Symptoms often appear in later stages and can include abdominal pain, weight loss, jaundice, and fatigue. Early detection improves treatment outcomes significantly.
column380: Avoid excessive drinking to reduce liver damage over time
column383: Practice safe hygiene and avoid needle sharing

column379: Lung contusion is a bruise of the lung tissue, usually caused by blunt chest trauma. The injury leads to bleeding and swelling within the lung, which can impair the exchange of oxygen. Symptoms may include chest pain, difficulty breathing, coughing up blood, or low oxygen levels. In severe cases, it can lead to respiratory failure and requires medical attention.
column380: Practice controlled and safe lifting techniques
column381: Avoid activities with high risk of falls
column382: Use protective gear during contact sports
column383: Wear seat belts while driving to help prevent chest trauma in case of accidents

column379: Magnesium deficiency, also known as hypomagnesemia, occurs when there’s not enough magnesium in the body. Magnesium is essential for muscle and nerve function, heart rhythm, and bone strength. A deficiency may lead to muscle cramps, fatigue, irregular heartbeat, mental confusion, or even seizures in severe cases. It can be caused by poor diet, certain medications, or underlying health issues.

Marijuana abuse refers to the excessive or problematic use of cannabis that interferes with daily life. It may lead to dependency, cognitive impairment, mood changes, and decreased motivation. Long-term abuse can affect mental health, memory, and overall productivity. While some use cannabis for medicinal or recreational purposes, abuse implies a pattern of misuse.
column380: Limit exposure to environments where it's used
column381: Stay engaged in physical activities or hobbies
column383: Seek support from peers or support groups

column379: Mastoiditis is an infection of the mastoid bone, located behind the ear. It often develops as a complication of untreated or severe middle ear infections (otitis media). The infection can lead to swelling, pain behind the ear, fever, and drainage from the ear. If not addressed, it may spread and cause serious complications like hearing loss or meningitis.
column380: Treat ear infections promptly with home care if mild
column381: Avoid inserting objects into the ears
column383: Stay hydrated and rest during colds

column379: Metabolic disorders refer to a group of conditions that affect how the body converts food into energy. These can involve issues with breaking down carbohydrates, fats, or proteins due to enzyme deficiencies or hormonal imbalances. Examples include diabetes, thyroid disorders, and inherited enzyme conditions. Symptoms vary but may include fatigue, weight changes, and developmental delays in children.
column380: Eat whole grains, fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins to support metabolism

column379: Mononucleosis, often called "mono," is a viral infection caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV). It typically affects teenagers and young adults and is characterized by fever, sore throat, swollen lymph nodes, and fatigue. The infection is spread through saliva but can also be transmitted through other bodily fluids.
column381: Drink fluids like water, herbal teas, and broth to prevent dehydration
column382: To prevent the spread of the virus, avoid close contact with others during the contagious period

column379: Myoclonus refers to the sudden, involuntary jerking or twitching of muscles. These muscle spasms can occur in one part of the body or involve the entire body. Myoclonus can be caused by various factors, including neurological disorders, medications, or metabolic disturbances. The severity and frequency of the jerks can vary.
column380: Identify and avoid any known triggers, such as stress, fatigue, or certain foods, that may worsen symptoms
column381: Engage in activities such as deep breathing, meditation, or gentle yoga to help reduce stress and muscle tension
column382: Prevent injuries by removing obstacles in your home and using support when moving around, as the jerks can cause loss of balance

column379: Myositis is the inflammation of the muscles, which can cause pain, weakness, and swelling. It can result from various factors, including autoimmune conditions, infections, or injuries. Common types include polymyositis, dermatomyositis, and infectious myositis. The inflammation can affect muscles throughout the body, leading to difficulty in movement and daily activities.
column382: Applying a warm compress or ice pack can help alleviate muscle pain and reduce inflammation

column379: Neonatal jaundice is a common condition in newborns where there is a yellowing of the skin and eyes due to high levels of bilirubin in the blood. It occurs because the liver of a newborn is still developing and may not be fully efficient in processing bilirubin. In most cases, it resolves on its own as the baby's liver matures, but sometimes it requires treatment like phototherapy.
column381: Keep an eye on the baby's skin and eyes for any further yellowing. If jaundice worsens or lasts longer, consult a pediatrician
column383: Regular pediatric check-ups ensure bilirubin levels are monitored

column379: Neuralgia refers to sharp, shooting pain along the course of a nerve, often caused by nerve irritation or damage. It can occur in various parts of the body, including the face (trigeminal neuralgia) or along the spine (postherpetic neuralgia). The pain can be intense and is typically triggered by activities such as touching the skin or certain movements. Common causes include infections, injuries, or conditions like diabetes.
column380: Identify and avoid activities or movements that trigger the pain, such as chewing or talking for facial neuralgia, or sudden head movements for neck or back neuralgia

column379: Nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) is a liver condition characterized by inflammation and damage to the liver cells, often caused by fat buildup in the liver. It occurs in people who drink little or no alcohol. NASH can lead to liver fibrosis (scarring), cirrhosis, and sometimes liver failure. It's commonly associated with obesity, type 2 diabetes, and high cholesterol. Symptoms may be absent initially, but as the condition progresses, fatigue, pain in the upper right abdomen, and jaundice may occur.
column381: Avoid high-fat and sugary foods. Incorporate more fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins into your diet to support liver health

column379: Normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH) is a condition where excess cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) builds up in the ventricles of the brain, causing them to enlarge. This can lead to pressure on the brain, which may result in symptoms such as difficulty walking, urinary incontinence, and cognitive problems (like memory loss or confusion). Despite the name, NPH can occur with normal pressure in the CSF. It is most common in older adults and can sometimes be misdiagnosed as Alzheimer's or Parkinson's disease.
column380: Monitor changes in balance and coordination

column379: Obesity is a condition characterized by excessive body fat accumulation that poses a risk to health. It is commonly defined by a body mass index (BMI) of 30 or higher. Obesity can lead to several health issues, including heart disease, diabetes, hypertension, and certain cancers. It is influenced by a combination of factors such as poor diet, lack of physical activity, genetics, and environmental influences.
column380: Focus on eating a variety of nutrient-dense foods, including fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains while limiting high-calorie, low-nutrient foods
column381: Engage in at least 30 minutes of moderate physical activity most days of the week

column379: An open wound on the back is a break in the skin that exposes underlying tissues, muscles, or organs. It can be caused by various factors, including trauma, accidents, or injuries. Open wounds require proper cleaning and care to prevent infection, and the severity of the wound will determine the treatment needed. Untreated open wounds can lead to complications like infection, scarring, or deeper tissue damage.
column381: Cover the wound with a sterile bandage
column382: Avoid touching the wound with dirty hands
column383: Watch for symptoms like increased redness, swelling, warmth, or pus around the wound. Seek medical attention if any of these signs occur

column379: An open wound on the neck refers to any break or tear in the skin or underlying tissues of the neck. This type of injury can be caused by trauma, cuts, accidents, or sharp objects. Open wounds in the neck are more concerning due to the proximity to vital structures like blood vessels, nerves, and the airway. Immediate care is crucial to prevent infection and severe complications. It may require medical attention, depending on the depth and severity.
column380: Apply direct pressure to control bleeding
column382: Cover the wound with a sterile dressing

column379: Oral leukoplakia is a condition characterized by the formation of white patches or plaques on the mucous membranes of the mouth, particularly on the tongue, gums, or inside of the cheeks. These patches cannot be scraped off and may sometimes be precancerous. While the exact cause isn't always clear, it is often associated with smoking, alcohol use, or irritation from dentures or rough teeth. It can sometimes develop into oral cancer, making early detection and management essential.

Osteochondrosis refers to a group of disorders that affect the growth of bones in children and adolescents. It involves the degeneration or softening of bone tissue, often in the joints. The condition commonly affects areas such as the knees, hips, and elbows. It can lead to pain, swelling, and restricted movement. While the exact cause is unclear, it is thought to be related to disruptions in blood flow to the growing bones, leading to cartilage damage. Osteochondrosis typically resolves with age, but in some cases, it may require medical intervention.

Otosclerosis is a condition that affects the bones of the middle ear, particularly the stapes bone. It causes abnormal bone growth that leads to hearing loss. The stapes bone becomes fixed in place, preventing it from vibrating properly and thus reducing sound transmission to the inner ear. This type of hearing loss is usually gradual and can be worsened by pregnancy or hormonal changes. Otosclerosis is most commonly inherited and affects women more often than men.
column383: Stay hydrated and maintain overall ear health

column379: Ovarian torsion occurs when an ovary twists around the ligaments that hold it in place, cutting off its blood supply. This can lead to severe pain and, if untreated, may cause permanent damage to the ovary. It is often associated with ovarian cysts, which can make the ovary more prone to twisting. Symptoms include sudden, severe abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Ovarian torsion is a medical emergency and requires prompt treatment, typically surgery, to untwist the ovary and restore blood flow.
column380: Seek immediate medical attention for sudden severe abdominal pain
column382: Monitor for symptoms of ovarian cysts

column379: Panic disorder is a type of anxiety disorder characterized by recurrent and unexpected panic attacks. A panic attack is an episode of intense fear or discomfort that reaches its peak within minutes, often accompanied by physical symptoms such as rapid heartbeat, sweating, dizziness, chest pain, and difficulty breathing. These attacks can occur without warning and may lead to avoidance behaviors, where individuals start fearing situations where a panic attack might happen. With proper treatment, panic disorder can be managed, often through therapy, medication, or a combination of both.
column380: Practice deep breathing and relaxation techniques

column379: Pelvic organ prolapse occurs when one or more of the pelvic organs (such as the bladder, uterus, or rectum) drop from their normal position and bulge into the vagina. This can happen due to weakness or stretching of the pelvic floor muscles, often as a result of childbirth, aging, or increased pressure on the pelvic area from obesity or chronic constipation. Symptoms can include a feeling of heaviness or fullness in the pelvic area, urinary incontinence, or difficulty with bowel movements. Treatment options may include pelvic floor exercises, pessary devices, or surgery in more severe cases.
column383: Stay hydrated and maintain regular bowel habits

Pericarditis is inflammation of the pericardium, the sac-like membrane surrounding the heart. This condition can result from various causes, including viral infections, bacterial infections, autoimmune diseases, or as a complication of a heart attack. Symptoms typically include sharp chest pain, often relieved by sitting up and leaning forward, shortness of breath, and fever. In some cases, pericarditis may cause fluid buildup around the heart, leading to further complications. Treatment often includes anti-inflammatory medications, pain relief, and addressing the underlying cause.
column381: Stay hydrated and eat a balanced diet

column379: Peritonitis is the inflammation of the peritoneum, the thin layer of tissue that lines the inside of the abdomen and covers abdominal organs. It is often caused by bacterial or fungal infections, typically resulting from an infection in the abdomen (such as appendicitis, a perforated ulcer, or diverticulitis), but it can also be a complication of surgery or injury. Symptoms include severe abdominal pain, bloating, fever, nausea, and vomiting. Peritonitis is a medical emergency that requires immediate treatment to prevent widespread infection. Treatment often involves antibiotics and sometimes surgery to remove the source of infection.
column383: If you experience worsening abdominal pain, fever, or other unusual symptoms, it’s important to seek immediate medical attention to prevent complications

column379: A pilonidal cyst is a fluid-filled sac that typically forms near the tailbone at the top of the buttocks. It can become infected and painful, leading to a condition known as pilonidal disease. The cyst often contains hair and debris and can develop when hair follicles become clogged. It is most common in individuals who spend long hours sitting or in those with thick body hair. Symptoms may include redness, swelling, and the formation of a small, painful lump. In severe cases, drainage or surgical removal may be required.

Pinworm infection is caused by a small parasitic worm called Enterobius vermicularis. It primarily affects children, though adults can also get infected. The main symptom is itching around the anus, especially at night when the female pinworms lay their eggs. The infection spreads easily through contact with contaminated surfaces or hands, and it can be contracted by ingesting eggs from contaminated food, water, or objects. The condition is usually treated with medication to kill the worms and prevent reinfection.
column382: Change bed linens and pajamas regularly

column379: A pituitary adenoma is a benign (non-cancerous) tumor that develops in the pituitary gland, which is located at the base of the brain. The pituitary gland produces hormones that regulate various body functions, and the tumor can affect hormone production, leading to symptoms such as unexplained weight gain or loss, fatigue, headaches, vision problems, or changes in menstrual cycles. Depending on its size and the hormones it produces, the tumor can cause a variety of health issues, but many people with pituitary adenomas may not experience symptoms.
column380: Keep track of any changes in vision, headaches, or other unusual symptoms and consult with a healthcare provider if any new symptoms arise
column383: Never take over-the-counter medications or supplements without consulting a healthcare provider, as some may interfere with hormone levels or exacerbate symptoms

column379: Experiencing chills, fatigue, a persistent cough, a high fever, and difficulty breathing. Sweating profusely, feeling unwell and weak. Chest aches when coughing, with the heart racing. The mucus being coughed up has a brownish, reddish, or black tint and is thick and stringy. Breathing is labored and uncomfortable, and there's an overwhelming amount of mucus in the throat. The rapid heartbeat continues with chest pain, and there's a sense of exhaustion and discomfort. The phlegm is often dark in color, resembling rust or black, indicating the severity of the condition.
column383: Ensure you're eating a balanced diet, exercising regularly, and getting enough sleep to help your body fight off infections

column379: Poisoning due to analgesics occurs when a person consumes an excessive amount of pain-relieving medications, either intentionally or accidentally. Analgesics, such as acetaminophen, ibuprofen, or opioids, are commonly used to treat pain, but an overdose can lead to serious health complications. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, confusion, difficulty breathing, and, in severe cases, liver damage, kidney failure, or even death.
column381: Do not take multiple types of pain medications simultaneously unless instructed by a doctor, especially over-the-counter (OTC) and prescription drugs
column382: Keep painkillers out of reach of children and store them in a cool, dry place to prevent accidental ingestion
column383: If you need to use analgesics for prolonged periods, consult with a healthcare provider to ensure safe usage and avoid dependency

column379: Poisoning due to antidepressants occurs when a person ingests a harmful amount of antidepressant medication, either intentionally or accidentally. Antidepressants, including selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs), and monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs), are used to treat depression and other mental health conditions. Overdose symptoms may include confusion, agitation, hallucinations, seizures, irregular heartbeat, or even loss of consciousness. Severe poisoning can lead to life-threatening conditions, such as serotonin syndrome or cardiac arrest.
column380: Never adjust the dosage of the prescribed antidepressants on your own.
column381: Do not mix antidepressants with alcohol or other recreational drugs, as this can increase the risk of severe side effects and overdose
column382: Keep antidepressants in a safe place away from children, and make sure that the bottles are tightly closed to avoid accidental ingestion
column383: If you experience unusual symptoms or mood changes while on antidepressants, contact your healthcare provider immediately for advice and further assessment

column379: Ethylene glycol poisoning happens when a person ingests a toxic amount of ethylene glycol — a chemical commonly found in antifreeze, brake fluid, and some industrial solvents. It has a sweet taste but is highly poisonous. Once ingested, it is broken down into harmful substances that can affect the brain, heart, and kidneys. Symptoms may start with nausea, vomiting, and confusion, and later progress to rapid breathing, seizures, or even coma if untreated.
column382: Wear gloves and work in well-ventilated areas when handling substances containing ethylene glycol
column383: Clearly label all chemical containers and dispose of any unused or expired products properly to avoid accidental poisoning

column379: Polycystic Kidney Disease is a genetic disorder characterized by the growth of numerous fluid-filled cysts in the kidneys. These cysts can enlarge the kidneys and impair their function over time, potentially leading to kidney failure. PKD may be inherited in an autosomal dominant or recessive pattern and can also affect other organs such as the liver. Symptoms include high blood pressure, back or side pain, abdominal fullness, and blood in the urine.
column382: Reduce sodium and processed foods to ease the burden on the kidneys

column379: Postpartum Depression is a type of mood disorder associated with childbirth. It typically arises within the first few weeks after delivery but can occur any time within the first year. It goes beyond the “baby blues” and includes symptoms like deep sadness, fatigue, irritability, trouble bonding with the baby, feelings of guilt or worthlessness, and even thoughts of self-harm or harming the baby. PPD can affect both mothers and, in rare cases, fathers.
column383: Eat regularly, stay mildly active, and avoid isolating yourself

column379: Presbyacusis is the gradual loss of hearing that occurs as people get older. It typically affects both ears and involves difficulty hearing high-pitched sounds, following conversations (especially in noisy environments), or needing the TV or radio louder than others. It results from changes in the inner ear and auditory nerve due to aging, and is one of the most common conditions affecting older adults.

Priapism is a prolonged and often painful erection of the penis that lasts for hours and occurs without sexual stimulation. It can be caused by blood disorders (like sickle cell anemia), medications, or injury. If not treated promptly, priapism can lead to permanent tissue damage and erectile dysfunction due to the lack of blood flow.
column380: Stay away from substances like cocaine or marijuana that may trigger episodes

column379: Primary insomnia is a sleep disorder where a person has trouble falling asleep, staying asleep, or waking up too early, i.e., without an identifiable medical, psychiatric, or environmental cause. It can lead to daytime fatigue, irritability, and reduced concentration. It’s often related to stress, irregular sleep schedules, or lifestyle factors.
column383: Keep electronics far from the bed

column379: This is a general term that can refer to any complication or issue arising during pregnancy, such as nausea, gestational diabetes, high blood pressure, anemia, or infections. While some are mild and manageable, others may require medical attention. Maintaining basic wellness can help support a healthy pregnancy.

Protein deficiency occurs when the body doesn’t get enough protein to meet its needs. It can lead to fatigue, muscle loss, weak immunity, swelling, and delayed wound healing. It’s more common in individuals with poor diets, certain health conditions, or malabsorption issues.
column381: Choose snacks like roasted chickpeas, yogurt, or nut butter on toast

column379: Psoriasis is a chronic skin condition where skin cells build up rapidly, causing scaling, redness, itching, and inflammation. It can come and go in cycles and may be triggered by stress, infections, or cold weather.
column381: Avoid skin irritants by wearing soft fabrics and use gentle soaps or cleansers
column383: Try light activities like deep breathing, walking, or listening to calming music to manage stress

column379: Pulmonary eosinophilia is a condition characterized by an increased number of eosinophils (a type of white blood cell) in the lungs, often causing coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath. It can be triggered by allergens, infections, or medications.
column381: Ventilate rooms well and consider an air purifier if needed

column379: Pulmonic valve disease occurs when the pulmonic valve, which regulates blood flow from the right ventricle to the lungs, doesn't function properly. This can lead to blood flow issues, causing symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, and chest pain.
column380: Avoid strenuous activities that may trigger shortness of breath

column379: Pyelonephritis is a bacterial infection of the kidneys that can cause symptoms like fever, chills, pain in the back or side, and urinary discomfort. It typically occurs when bacteria travel up the urinary tract to the kidneys, leading to inflammation and infection.

Pyloric stenosis is a condition in which the pylorus (the opening from the stomach to the small intestine) becomes narrowed due to thickening of the muscles, leading to vomiting, dehydration, and weight loss in infants. It is a common cause of projectile vomiting in young babies.
column383: Seek medical attention for severe vomiting

column379: Restless Leg Syndrome (RLS) is a neurological disorder that causes an irresistible urge to move the legs, typically due to uncomfortable sensations. These sensations are most noticeable when resting or lying down, and the symptoms often improve with movement. RLS can interfere with sleep and daily activities.

column1: retinopathy due to high blood pressure
column379: Retinopathy due to high blood pressure (hypertensive retinopathy) is damage to the retina of the eye caused by high blood pressure. The blood vessels in the retina become narrowed, thickened, or damaged, leading to vision problems. This condition can progress silently and is often detected during routine eye exams.
column381: Follow a heart-healthy diet which is low in sodium, saturated fats, and rich in fruits and vegetables

column379: A rotator cuff injury occurs when the tendons or muscles of the rotator cuff in the shoulder are torn or damaged. This can result from overuse, trauma, or aging. Symptoms include pain, weakness, and limited range of motion in the shoulder. It is common in athletes or individuals performing repetitive overhead movements.
column380: Refrain from activities that involve lifting or reaching above the head, as this can strain the shoulder

column379: Salivary gland disorders refer to any condition that affects the salivary glands, which produce saliva to help with digestion and oral hygiene. Common issues include infections, blockages, tumors, and dry mouth. Symptoms may include swelling, pain, dry mouth, or difficulty swallowing.

Sick sinus syndrome is a condition where the heart's natural pacemaker, the sinus node, doesn't function properly, leading to irregular heart rhythms (arrhythmias). It can cause symptoms like dizziness, fainting, fatigue, and palpitations. It is more common in older adults and may require medical intervention, including pacemaker implantation in severe cases.

Spondylitis is an inflammatory condition that affects the spine, causing pain, stiffness, and limited movement. It can involve the sacroiliac joints (where the lower spine meets the pelvis) and may also affect other joints. Over time, it can lead to the fusion of vertebrae, limiting flexibility. The most common form is ankylosing spondylitis, which primarily affects young adults.

Spondylosis is a degenerative condition that affects the spine, typically due to age-related wear and tear of the spinal discs and joints. It can cause pain, stiffness, and reduced mobility in the neck, back, or lower back. It is commonly referred to as spinal osteoarthritis and may lead to bone spurs and narrowing of the spaces between vertebrae.
column382: Choose chairs, desks, and sleeping positions that support the spine and reduce unnecessary pressure on the back
column383: Stay active and avoid prolonged sitting

column379: A stroke occurs when there is a sudden disruption in the blood supply to part of the brain. This can be due to a blockage (ischemic stroke) or a rupture of blood vessels (hemorrhagic stroke). Strokes can cause a wide range of symptoms, including sudden weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision problems, and loss of coordination. Quick medical intervention is crucial to minimize brain damage.

A subdural hemorrhage occurs when blood collects between the brain and the outer layer of the brain’s protective covering (the dura). This can happen due to a head injury or trauma, leading to increased pressure on the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, confusion, dizziness, nausea, and sometimes loss of consciousness. It requires immediate medical attention, and treatment may involve surgery depending on the severity.
column380: Always wear protective gear, such as helmets, while engaging in sports or activities with a risk of head trauma
column382: After any head injury, monitor for signs such as headaches, dizziness, or confusion

column379: Substance-related mental disorders are a group of conditions in which the use of drugs or alcohol causes significant changes in mood, thoughts, and behavior, leading to problems in daily functioning. Symptoms can include intense cravings, withdrawal symptoms, mood swings, impaired decision-making, and disturbances in cognitive functioning. Treatment often involves therapy, counseling, and, in some cases, medication to manage symptoms and cravings.
column383: Participate in hobbies, physical activities, and social events to reduce stress and maintain mental health without relying on substances

column379: Teething syndrome refers to the discomfort and symptoms that infants experience as their primary teeth begin to emerge through the gums. Symptoms can include irritability, drooling, gum swelling, and sometimes a mild fever. While teething is a normal developmental stage, it can cause temporary distress for both the baby and the parents.
column380: Gently massage your baby's gums with a clean finger or a soft cloth to soothe the discomfort
column382: Wipe your baby’s face often to prevent irritation from drool and to keep the skin clean

column379: A thoracic aortic aneurysm is a dilation or bulging in the part of the aorta that passes through the chest (thoracic aorta). This condition can be asymptomatic or cause symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, or back pain. If the aneurysm ruptures, it can be life-threatening. Regular monitoring and medical intervention are necessary to prevent complications.

Thrombophlebitis is the inflammation of a vein caused by a blood clot. It typically occurs in the legs, although it can develop in other parts of the body. Symptoms include redness, warmth, swelling, and pain along the affected vein. While often not dangerous, it can lead to more serious conditions if the clot breaks loose and travels to the lungs (pulmonary embolism).

Tietze syndrome is a rare inflammatory condition that affects the cartilage where the ribs attach to the sternum (breastbone). It is characterized by swelling and tenderness in the upper chest, often mistaken for a heart attack or other cardiac issues. The cause of Tietze syndrome is not fully understood, but it is generally self-limiting and can resolve over time.
column380: Refrain from activities that put strain on the chest area, as this can aggravate symptoms

column379: Tinnitus refers to the perception of ringing, buzzing, or other sounds in the ears without an external sound source. When the cause is unknown, it is often referred to as idiopathic tinnitus. It can occur due to a variety of factors, including exposure to loud noises, ear infections, or stress, though no clear cause can always be identified. The condition can be temporary or chronic and can be bothersome, affecting quality of life.
column381: Engage in relaxation techniques like deep breathing or meditation to minimize stress
column383: Use white noise to mask the ringing

column379: A transient ischemic attack (TIA), often called a "mini-stroke," occurs when blood flow to a part of the brain is temporarily interrupted. TIAs typically last only a few minutes and do not cause permanent brain damage. However, they serve as a warning sign of potential future strokes. Symptoms may include sudden weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, or loss of vision in one eye. Prompt medical attention is crucial to reduce the risk of a full-blown stroke.
column381: Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins while limiting processed foods, salt, and unhealthy fats

column379: Tuberous sclerosis is a genetic disorder that causes non-cancerous (benign) tumors to form in various organs, including the brain, kidneys, heart, eyes, and lungs. Symptoms can vary widely but may include developmental delays, seizures, skin abnormalities, and intellectual disabilities. The condition is caused by mutations in two genes (TSC1 and TSC2). While the severity of the disorder can differ from person to person, early diagnosis and management can help reduce complications and improve quality of life.
column381: Gently care for the skin to reduce the risk of developing painful growths or sores
column383: Keep up with routine medical appointments, especially with specialists, to monitor organ function and tumor development

column379: Turner syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects females, caused by the partial or complete absence of one of the X chromosomes. It leads to a variety of physical and developmental characteristics, including short stature, infertility, heart defects, and hearing problems. Affected individuals may also have learning disabilities, particularly in math and spatial reasoning, though intelligence is typically normal. Early diagnosis and medical management can help address many of the health concerns associated with the condition.
column380: Ensure adequate calcium and vitamin D intake and engage in weight-bearing exercises to maintain bone strength
column381: If fertility is a concern, seek advice from a healthcare provider who can discuss potential options and treatments
column382: Keep track of growth patterns, especially during childhood, to address any growth concerns early with your doctor

Urethral valves are abnormal folds of tissue found in the urethra, the tube that carries urine from the bladder out of the body. These valves can obstruct urine flow and cause a variety of urinary issues, including urinary retention, urinary tract infections (UTIs), and kidney damage if left untreated. Urethral valve obstruction is most commonly seen in males and can be diagnosed through imaging tests like ultrasound or cystoscopy. Treatment often involves surgery to remove the valves and restore normal urine flow.

Uterine fibroids are non-cancerous growths that develop in or around the uterus. They are made of muscle and fibrous tissue and can vary in size. While many women with fibroids experience no symptoms, others may face heavy menstrual bleeding, pelvic pain, or pressure on the bladder. Fibroids are often discovered during routine pelvic exams or ultrasound. Treatment options vary based on the size, symptoms, and location of the fibroids and can include medication, non-invasive procedures, or surgery.
column382: Focus on a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains to support overall reproductive health
column383: Be mindful of heavy menstrual bleeding, pelvic pain, or frequent urination, and seek medical advice if symptoms worsen or new symptoms develop

column379: A vaginal yeast infection, also known as candidiasis, is caused by an overgrowth of the fungus Candida. This condition can lead to itching, burning, and abnormal discharge from the vagina. While yeast infections are common and typically not serious, they can be uncomfortable and may recur in some individuals. Factors like antibiotic use, hormonal changes, or a weakened immune system can increase the risk of developing a yeast infection.
column383: Consider incorporating probiotics into your diet

column379: Vaginitis is the inflammation of the vaginal lining that can result from various causes, including infections, allergic reactions, or irritations. Common symptoms include itching, burning, unusual discharge, and discomfort during urination or intercourse. It can be caused by bacterial infections, yeast infections, sexually transmitted infections (STIs), or even hygiene products that cause irritation.
column380: Avoid using scented soaps, feminine sprays, and douches as these can irritate the vaginal area and upset the natural pH balance
